xxl.core.collections.queues
Interface Queue<E>

Type Parameters:
E - the type of the elements of this queue.
All Known Subinterfaces:
FIFOQueue<E>, LIFOQueue<E>, MemoryManageableQueue<E>
All Known Implementing Classes:
AbstractMemoryManageableQueue, AbstractQueue, ArrayQueue, BlockBasedQueue, BoundedQueue, CounterRandomAccessFileQueue, DecoratorQueue, DistinctQueue, DynamicHeap, FileStackQueue, Heap, ListQueue, ListStreamQueue, MemoryManageableListQueue, RandomAccessFileQueue, StackQueue, StreamQueue, ThreadsafeQueue, UnmodifiableQueue
public interface Queue<E>

The interface queue represents an user specified iteration over a collection of elements (also known as a sequence) with a peek method. This interface does not predefine any strategy for addition and removal of elements so that the user has full control concerning his strategy (e.g., FIFO (first in, first out), LIFO (last in, first out) etc.).

In contrast to sets, queues typically allow duplicate elements. More formally, queues typically allow pairs of elements e1 and e2 such that e1.equals(e2), and they typically allow multiple null elements if they allow null elements at all.

It is important to see that the peek method only shows the element which currently is the next element. The next call of dequeue does not have to return the peeked element. This is a difference to the semantic of peek inside the Cursor interface.

Field Detail

FACTORY_METHOD

static final Function<Object,ArrayQueue<Object>> FACTORY_METHOD
A factory method to create a default queue. Each concrete implementation of a queue except for ArrayQueue should have a function FACTORY_METHOD that implements three variants of invoke
  • Queue invoke():
    • returns new Queue().
  • Queue invoke(Object iterator):
    • returns new Queue(iterator).
  • Queue invoke(List internalDataStructure):
    • returns new Queue((<InternalDataStructure>)internalDataStructure.get(0)).
This factory method creates a new ArrayQueue. It may be invoked with a parameter list (for further details see Function) of object arrays, an iterator or without any parameters. A parameter list of object arrays will be used to initialize the internally used array with the object array at index 0 and an iterator will be used to insert the contained elements into the new ArrayQueue.

Function
Method Detail

open

void open()
Opens the queue, i.e., signals the queue to reserve resources, open files, etc. Before a queue has been opened calls to methods like peek are not guaranteed to yield proper results. Therefore open must be called before a queue's data can be processed. Multiple calls to open do not have any effect, i.e., if open was called the queue remains in the state opened until its close method is called.

Note, that a call to the open method of a closed queue usually does not open it again because of the fact that its state generally cannot be restored when resources are released respectively files are closed.

close

void close()
Closes this queue and releases any system resources associated with it. This operation is idempotent, i.e., multiple calls of this method take the same effect as a single call.
Note that this method is very important for queues using external resources like files or JDBC resources.

enqueue

             throws IllegalStateException
Appends the specified element to the end of this queue. The end of the queue is given by its strategy.

object - element to be appended at the end of this queue.
Throws:

peek

E peek()
       throws IllegalStateException,
              NoSuchElementException
Returns the element which currently is the next element in the queue. The element is not removed from the queue (in contrast to the method dequeue). The next element of the queue is given by its strategy. The next call to dequeue does not have to return the element which was returned by peek.

Returns:
the next element in the queue.
Throws:
IllegalStateException - if the queue is already closed when this method is called.
NoSuchElementException - queue has no more elements.

dequeue

E dequeue()
          throws IllegalStateException,
                 NoSuchElementException
Returns the next element in the queue and removes it. The next element of the queue is given by its strategy.

Returns:
the next element in the queue.
Throws:
IllegalStateException - if the queue is already closed when this method is called.
NoSuchElementException - queue has no more elements.

isEmpty

boolean isEmpty()
Returns false if the queue has more elements (in other words, returns false if next would return an element rather than throwing an exception).

Returns:
false if the queue has more elements.

size

int size()
Returns the number of elements in this queue. If this queue contains more than Integer.MAX_VALUE elements, returns Integer.MAX_VALUE.

Returns:
the number of elements in this queue.

clear

void clear()
Removes all of the elements from this queue. The queue will be empty after this call returns so that size() == 0.
Note that the elements will only be removed from the queue but not from the underlying collection.
